<HL>
   Who's News:
   Medical Journal's Relman
   Plans to Retire Next Year
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   WALTHAM, Mass. -- Arnold S. Relman, editor in chief of the
New England Journal of Medicine, announced plans to retire
from the post next June.
   Dr. Relman, 67 years old, was named editor of the medical
journal in 1977 and assumed his current post in 1988. In
announcing his decision, he said he plans to devote himself
"more to writing and teaching, and to participate more fully
in public policy debates on American health care." Dr. Relman
is also a part-time professor at Harvard Medical School.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The New England Journal of Medicine is published by the
Massachusetts Medical Society. As the journal's chief, Dr.
Relman is one of the nation's most prominent doctors. His
views have helped shape medical opinions and policies at a
time when the health-care system has undergone rapid changes.
   During his tenure, the journal has emphasized issues of
broad medical and scientific interest. Among other things, it
published articles that helped identify and explain acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, toxic shock syndrome and
Legionnaires' disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0159
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0159.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Stone Container Corp.
   Lines Up $400 Million
   In Standby Financing
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   STO
</CO>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Stone Container Corp. said banks are willing to
lend it an additional $400 million, an amount that could help
it ride out an earnings slump and repay other debt coming due
in September.
   Investors appeared to welcome Stone's announcement of
additional financing. The paper and packaging company's stock
closed at $17, up 87.5 cents, in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stone grew rapidly over the past five years, mostly by
making acquisitions with borrowed money. After its biggest
and most recent purchase, the $2.2 billion takeover of
Consolidated-Bathurst Inc. in 1989, Stone emerged as the
second-largest paper company in North America.
   But Stone's business outlook has weakened this year amid a
general downturn in the paper industry, and the company
reported a 58% drop in first-quarter earnings. In recent
weeks, Wall Street analysts have been cutting their earnings
estimates for Stone "pretty severely," says Robert Schifini,
a researcher at Institutional/Brokers/Estimate/System.
   Arnold Brookstone, Stone's chief financial officer, said
the new $400 million standby credit facility "isn't an
expression of any inability to make our payments. We are a
very conservative company. We believe in planning for
contingencies before anything happens."
   In recent weeks, attention has focused on Stone's
scheduled repayment of its $2.6 billion in senior long-term
debt, much of which was taken on to pay for the
Consolidated-Bathurst acquisition. Although Stone has been
able to make interest payments with ease, it also is
obligated in September to repay $175 million of its bank
debt, with more repayments to follow.
   The new credit facility, Mr. Brookstone said, provides an
additional possible source of cash to make its $175 million
debt repayment this year. He said the repayments could also
be made from operating cash flow or by temporarily borrowing
more money under a bank revolving-credit facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0158
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0158.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Destructive Viruses
   Have Now Spread
   To Japanese PCs
   ----
   By Jacob M. Schlesinger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NIPNY J.SRP J.FUT JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Personal computer viruses, virtually unheard of a
few years ago in Japan, are spreading here, government and
industry officials fear.
   NEC Corp., Japan's largest PC maker, announced this week
that an unspecified number of its flagship 9800-series models
are infected with a "Christmas" virus that can wipe out
certain large application programs when the computer's
calendar reaches Dec. 25.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In April, Sharp Corp. said a game program compatible with
its X-68000 PC was infected with a virus, and press reports
said about half the 3,000 programs sold were tainted. In May,
Fujitsu Ltd. discovered a virus in 20 on-site computers that
would become active on any Friday the 13th.
   "Those three cases may be a warning," said Shinjuro Ogino,
director of the software technology center of the
government-affiliated Information-Technology Promotion
Agency. "I'm afraid there will be an increase of computer
viruses for Japanese personal computers."
   Japan has lagged far behind other developed nations in
personal computer use, but sales are now taking off, and with
the growing popularity may come growing computer crime.
   An agency survey of nearly 400 Japanese companies reported
only one virus complaint in 1986, two in 1987, and seven in
1988. But the survey showed 30 complaints in 1989, and six in
the first three months of 1990. Mr. Ogino said most of those
cases involved machines imported from the U.S., where viruses
are far more common. He said he worried that the recent
viruses may have targeted Japanese machines specifically.
   Fujitsu and NEC said the cases announced this year were
the most serious they had ever found.
   In the NEC virus, when the computer's calendar turns to
Dec. 25, the words "A Merry Christmas to You]" appear on the
screen, and applications larger than 30,720 bytes are
destroyed.
   Sharp discovered two similar viruses in programs for the
computer game Farside Moon for its machines. One strain,
designed to turn on once a month beginning this month, is
supposed to destroy data on the floppy disk and could also
damage the machine's components, according to Japanese press
reports.
   The Fujitsu virus gradually expands to fill the computer's
memory and prevent the PC's use. On a Friday the 13th, which
occurs this week, the application program is destroyed.
   Spokesmen for Fujitsu and NEC said no damage had been
done. A Sharp spokesman couldn't be reached for comment.
   "Software delivered by the software vendors or
manufacuters is okay," said a Fujitsu spokesman, but
"software is becoming more popular to share among colleauges,
so there's more possibility that the virus move from one PC
to another PC."
   But an official in the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry who is following the issue said the number of
reported cases may be increasing simply because of greater
awareness. "I think in past days, people regarded some
trouble as bugs and not as a virus."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0157
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0157.
</DOCID>
