<HL>
   Computer Firms
   Expected to Post
   Mixed Results
   ---
   Makers of Desktop Machines
   Prospering, Analysts Say,
   But Others in Slowdown
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder and G. Pascal Zachary
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4A
</SO>
<CO>
   DEC SUNW UIS IBM AAPL SQNT TDM PYRD CPQ
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The gap between the haves and the have-nots continues to
widen in the computer industry.
   Analysts say results for the June quarter will provide
fresh evidence that companies making desktop computers are
prospering while makers of traditional machines, such as
mainframes and minicomputers, are posting smaller gains or
even losing business.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Consider the contrast between Digital Equipment Corp. and
Sun Microsystems Inc. Digital, once a high-flier and a Wall
Street darling, is expected to post a 50% earnings drop for
its fiscal fourth quarter ended June 30. Analysts, meantime,
expect Sun to show a profit of as much as $47 million for its
fiscal fourth quarter, compared to a year-earlier loss.
   The key difference: Sun sells desktop workstations and
networking computers; Digital still depends heavily on
expensive minicomputers. "DEC isn't competitive on the
desktop," where the growth and profits are, says analyst
Robert Herwick at Hambrecht &amp; Quist. "DEC is just not there,
whereas Sun is very much there."
   The story holds true among other makers of desktop
machines, both workstations and personal computers. Analyst
Michelle Preston of Cowen &amp; Co. estimates that Apple Computer
Inc.'s net income in its fiscal third quarter ended June 30
rose more than 15% to $114 million, or 90 cents a share, and
that revenue increased 10% to $1.4 billion. Compaq Computer
Corp.'s profit for the June quarter, she predicts, grew 21%
to $102 million, or $2.30 a share, on a 28% rise in revenue
to $926 million.
   Sun's expected healthy gains apparently confirm its
rebound from last year's painful manufacturing and
product-transition snafus. Peter Rogers, an analyst at
Robertson Stephens &amp; Co., estimates that Sun will earn $47
million, or 50 cents a share, on revenue of $700 million. In
the year-ago period, Sun had a loss of $20.3 million on sales
of $431 million.
   Sun's rebound was fueled by improved operations and new
computers that are eating away at the competition in the
burgeoning market for workstations, machines used by
engineers and scientists. "Sun finds itself in a very strong
leadership position in the workstation market despite
everybody else all taking their best shots," says Mr.
Herwick, the Hambrecht &amp; Quist analyst.
   Growth comes harder for computer companies that depend on
sales of more expensive machines. International Business
Machines Corp., for instance, is the largest maker of
personal computers but because it relies heavily on sales of
larger computers it is expected to show slowing growth.
Analyst Daniel Benton of Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. estimates that
Big Blue's second-quarter revenue grew only 6% to $16.2
billion. Net income is expected to be down 7% to $1.3
billion, or $2.20 a share, he said.
   The earnings picture is even more dismal for Unisys Corp.,
which depends more heavily on sales of expensive computers
than IBM. Mr. Benton estimates that Unisys will break even
for the quarter on slightly lower revenue, which he expects
to total $2.5 billion. "The picture is scary," said Mr.
Benton. "Unisys isn't showing any signs of rebound."
   Unisys earned $27 million in the year-ago period and Mr.
Benton believes it's possible the firm lost money in this
year's June quarter, its second of the fiscal year. "We may
see another restructuring of (the company) before year end,"
he said.
   In addition to its poor showing in the desktop market,
Digital was hurt by production glitches in its VAX-9000
minicomputers, says analyst Barry Willman of Sanford C.
Bernstein &amp; Co. He estimates Digital earned about $155
million, or $1.25 a share, in the June quarter, down from
$313.2 million, or $2.51 a share, last year. Mr. Willman
estimated revenue at about $3.4 billion, down from $3.49
billion.
   Not all makers of more expensive machines will be hurting.
Companies such as Sequent Computer Systems Inc., Tandem
Computers Inc. and Pyramid Technology Corp. are expected to
benefit from a move by banks, financial institutions and
other computer users toward on-line processing systems. Those
systems perform such tasks as credit-card verifications and
run automated teller machines.
   Tandem's net income should rise about 55% in the fiscal
third quarter ended June 30 to $48 million, or 43 cents a
share, from $30.8 million a year ago, or 31 cents a share,
estimates analyst John Jones of Montgomery Securities.
Revenue will grow 24% to $520 million in the quarter, he
says.
   Hambrecht &amp; Quist expects Sequent's net income in the
period to rise 56% to $5.4 million, or 23 cents a share, on
revenue of about $54 million, up 73% from the year-ago
period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0136
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0136.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   If This Show Isn't Another Bomb,
   They'll Do `Back to Grenada' Next
   ----
   By Bill Richards
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   TACOMA, Wash. -- Every action epic has a sequel these
days, so it should be no surprise that the Air Force is
producing "Panama II."
   Military officials at McChord AFB here thought they had a
swell idea to help celebrate the military airfield's 50th
anniversary. "The most spectacular event scheduled,"
trumpeted a McChord news release last month, "will be a joint
services re-enactment of the invasion of Panama. The actual
aircraft, aircrews and soldiers who were there
participating]"
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But as with the original, there have been problems with
the sequel.
   Local newspapers began calling the exercise, scheduled for
this Sunday, a "pseudo invasion." And there were also some
troublesome details: Who would play Gen. Manuel Noriega? How
would several hundred Panamanians be tastefully done away
with?
   To simplify matters, Air Force officials decided to leave
Panamanians out of the new invasion altogether, and McChord's
public-relations staff was ordered to stop mentioning the
original locale.
   "Our guys will parachute in, deploy on the ground and then
walk into the crowd and shake a few hands," says Maj. Morris
Bedard, the Air Force impresario who dreamed up the concept
of a second Panamanian go-around. "They're calling me Cecil
B. de Mille the second," he boasts. The idea behind the
concept: "To let the taxpayers see what it is that we do
around here."
   With or without Gen. Noriega and his countrymen, the
re-enactment will have plenty of action. Hundreds of
paratroopers will drop onto the base runway in front of
thousands of expected onlookers. "The real spectacular part
will be the strafing runs by the fighter planes," Maj. Bedard
says. The planes are scheduled to swoop in over the crowd and
blast away at the nonexistent Panamanian enemy.
   Reminded that when the Air Force dispatched a Stealth
fighter to Panama to do just that during the real thing, the
plane missed its target, Maj. Bedard says: "We won't have any
Stealths." Besides, he says, the fighters will be shooting
blanks.
   Without ammunition, a location or half the original cast,
can the Air Force's sequel live up to the original? Maj.
Bedard dismisses the question with a de Mille-like shrug. "I
wasn't there," he says. "I came up with the concept. It was
up to the flyboys to restage the thing right."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0135
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0135.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Jazz:
   My Daughter the Musician
   ----
   By Nat Hentoff
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<LP>
   The tent in which the Great South Bay Jazz Festival had
been held was nearly empty. The only musician left was tenor
saxophonist and arranger Al Cohn. Walking toward the exit, we
were talking about the players -- Coleman Hawkins, Rex
Stewart, J.C. Higginbotham. All had been, to use Hawkins's
phrase, "full of the spirit." I had been listening to them
since I was 12 years old, and I knew I'd always be listening
to them.
   "Sure," Cohn said, "We're most comfortable with the music
we've grown up on. You try to get with the new sounds, but
when you're by yourself, you play Billie Holiday and Lester
Young and Count Basie."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That conversation took place a little more than 30 years
ago. Even then, I realized -- though I was much taken with
the startling new sounds of John Coltrane and Cecil Taylor --
that it was Duke Ellington I played late at night when I was
no longer working as a critic.
   Writing about the music had been the only way I could
become part of it. I had been a classical clarinetist since
childhood, but I couldn't improvise worth a damn. My fantasy
had been to be hired by Duke Ellington and, bowing, to take a
seat alongside Johnny Hodges. But I finally acknowledged that
I'd have to go into another line of work, off the bandstand.
   I had another fantasy -- that one of my children might
become so striking a jazz musician as to be hired by
Ellington or Basie. Now I have four children. One is a circus
performer and the other two are in law. But Miranda is a
musician -- a pianist, singer and composer . . .
   In the early stages of her obsession with music, she may
well have listened to every recording that jazz pianist Bill
Evans had ever made, along with an abundance of Billie
Holiday, Sarah Vaughan and Duke Ellington. And she was "full
of the spirit" when she played gigs.
   At first, those engagements were in Chinese restaurants,
where a number of jazz musicians, through the decades, have
served apprenticeships. Then there were dates at jazz clubs
where the food wasn't as good, but the audience sometimes
actually listened.
   Meanwhile, she got a master's degree in education at the
Manhattan School of Music, to make sure she'd be able to pay
the rent. She then taught for four years at the Harlem School
of the Arts, and continues to be a "teacher artist" at
Lincoln Center as well as at a number of public schools,
including magnet schools, in and out of New York.
   But, always, her eye was on the performance prize. Hearing
her in clubs, I started thinking that rather than work in
Basie's band, she ought to go on the road with her own combo.
She already was talking like a jazz musician. Reading some of
my reviews of various players, she'd shake her head and say:
"How can you criticize somebody else's performance when you
can't play yourself?" That reminded me of Horace Silver, the
gentlest of jazz pianists off the stand, saying to me years
ago when I worked for Down Beat magazine, "You wrote that I
play `angular' piano. What the hell is that? Can you show me
how to play `angular' piano?"
   Going to some of her gigs, I began to hear that jazz was
less and less on her mind. And she was singing more. It is
her most immediately identifiable sound, dark and resonant.
All the songs were her own, and most were about largely
unrequited love. Her other songs were just plain funny and
self-deprecating.
   Okay, I thought, even though there's not much cabaret
anymore, she can, over time, build up a small but steady
following of listeners who can't stand what's on the radio.
The kind of urbane audience that used to stay for both sets
of Mabel Mercer, and has had hardly anywhere else to go
since.
   But then there was another change. She plunged into rock.
I could no longer hear the lyrics, but I sure could hear the
synthesizers. I told her she had gone into territory far
beyond my ken.
   It wasn't my fault, she told me. It's the way people of my
generation hear music. She and people of her generation
listen in a fundamentally different way so far as textures,
rhythms, the inner meanings of words, and especially feelings
are concerned. Different generations, Dad, look for different
kinds of emotions in music.
   I was too old, in sum, to know when a synthesizer was
singing to me. I tried Ellington's apothegm: "There are only
two kinds of music -- good and bad."
   "To whom?" she said.
   Well, I figured, she's changed before, maybe she'll change
again. On two nights in recent months, I heard her in
Greenwich Village clubs with her new combo, the Miranda
Hentoff Band. I liked seeing that in print, but I wondered if
they swung at all.
   It's not jazz, but these players are musicians, a
description that can be applied to many rock players only
with highly irresponsible kindness. On keyboards, guitar,
bass and drums, the proudly disciplined members of Miranda's
band, who do a lot of studio work on their own, play with
crisp, often exhilarating drive.
   The singer, who also plays acoustic and electric piano
with elan (and no angularity), still features her own songs.
But now I can hear the lyrics again ("I used to think that
time is all you need/Finally I see how many ways you leave").
   As the music spiraled on, I was tapping my foot, like
people of my generation do. This would be a good band to take
on the road, I was thinking. It doesn't have to be jazz to
make people feel good. What they need is a recording date.
   Now there's a refrain that bridges musical generations,
with plenty of feeling.
   ---
   Mr. Hentoff is a New York-based writer and jazz critic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
