<HL>
   Who's News:
   Cray President Gumucio Packs His Bags
   As Chairman Cites Conflicting Styles
   ----
   By Richard Gibson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CYR WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- Cray Research Inc.'s president and chief
operating officer, Marcelo A. Gumucio, is leaving the
supercomputer maker because of disagreements with the
chairman on how to carry out a strategy they jointly
developed.
   "This wasn't spurred by an event," said John A. Rollwagen,
chairman and chief executive officer. Mr. Rollwagen said he
decided Mr. Gumucio should go because their different
management styles were "creating confusion" within the ranks.
"We're on track -- in total agreement about our strategy.
It's the style issue that makes it rather squishy."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Style" is a key word at Cray, which has painstakingly
created a work environment designed to foster creativity in a
highly competitive leading-edge technology. Seymour R. Cray,
its flannel-shirted founder, started the company in the woods
of western Wisconsin after fleeing the bureaucracy of a large
company.
   As the Japanese shortened the U.S. lead in supercomputing,
Mr. Rollwagen apparently came to believe that the company
could ill afford delays because of what he called "mixed
signals" from top management. "We needed some clarity," he
said.
   The departure of Mr. Gumucio, 52 years old, is Cray's
third major personnel jolt in as many years. In 1987 Steve
Chen, the architect of Cray's best-selling machines, left in
a dispute over technical directions. Then, Mr. Cray left the
company last year, when his latest research project -- which
Mr. Gumucio and others saw as an increasing drain on company
resources -- was spun off.
   Yesterday Mr. Rollwagen, in an interview, drew a parallel
between the Chen and Gumucio departures; both men represented
challenges to the "Cray style." While Mr. Rollwagen practices
what he calls an "intuitive" style, he said Mr. Gumucio
represented a "more formal, structured approach" that the two
found increasingly in conflict.
   Last Monday, after they had been away for several weeks,
the two men got together and agreed that a change was
necessary, both said.
   Disputes with the boss aren't unusual, but Mr. Gumucio's
departure is. Although his resignation as an officer and
director was immediate, Mr. Gumucio spent much of yesterday
in his office, explaining to visitors the "philosophical
differences" that led to what he called an "irreconcilable
divorce." In an adjacent office, Mr. Rollwagen was doing the
same.
   The 49-year-old chairman said he would assume many of Mr.
Gumucio's duties, but has no immediate plans to name a
successor. "We don't have to have a president," he said.
   Mr. Gumucio was named president in November 1988, as
recognition of his success in leading Cray's marketing
efforts world-wide, and because his bottom-line orientation
was seen as helping the company cope with a period of slower
growth.
   Analysts credit Mr. Gumucio with convincing the company to
make a smaller, less expensive supercomputer so as to broaden
sales prospects. That machine is due out shortly. He also is
considered a key architect of Cray's effort to plug its
machines into more computer networks world-wide. Mr. Gumucio
takes credit as well for the decision to spin off Mr. Cray's
project.
   "We have a great strategy that we've carved out," Mr.
Gumucio said yesterday, contending it will take the company
into the 21st century. But differences over the timing of
those plans led to growing disagreements with Mr. Rollwagen,
he said. "I'm more of a pusher than John is," Mr. Gumucio
said. "He allows a little more time."
   Mr. Gumucio also was more demanding in holding the sales
force to quotas, and over such nuts-and-bolts issues as
compensation -- matters that eventually got back to Mr.
Rollwagen, who in recent months had been spending more time
making the rounds of the company.
   Gary P. Smaby, a Minneapolis-based supercomputer industry
consultant, said the management change "should say to
customers that the company has again indicated its intention
to stay on target." But he also predicted that Mr.
Rollwagen's "style will have to evolve to adapt to the
market."
   Mr. Gumucio said he has no plans to sell his Cray stock,
which amounted to 8,957 shares as of the most recent proxy
statement. Cray closed yesterday at $48, up 62.5 cents in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   A native of Bolivia, Mr. Gumucio is a naturalized U.S.
citizen. He joined Cray in 1983 from Northern Telecom Ltd.,
where he was executive vice president, marketing. Previously,
he worked for Memorex Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0129
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0129.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Federal Express
   Posts 5% Increase
   In Quarterly Profit
   ----
   By Peter Waldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   FDX
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AIR FREIGHT (AIF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Federal Express Corp. said it had a slight increase in net
income in its fiscal fourth quarter, ended May 31, but it
reported a drop in operating profit, reflecting continued
losses overseas.
   The Memphis, Tenn.-based air-express concern reported net
income of $43.1 million, or 81 cents a share, up 5% from $41
million, or 78 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue climbed
15% to $1.91 billion from $1.67 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the earnings gain, Federal's first year-to-year profit
growth since November 1988, masks some underlying problems.
Federal's operating profit declined 7% in the period. It is
still being hurt by its attempts to expand abroad, and a
sudden downturn in its domestic business in recent months is
compounding its problems.
   "The sluggishness in the domestic economy is showing up
and they don't see any pickup," said Kevin Murphy, a
transportation analyst with Morgan Stanley. "This is a
company in the throes of a transition to a new type of
business. It's still a good game plan, but I don't see any
reasonable signs that it's bearing fruit right now."
   Federal was able to report a profit boost in the quarter,
despite the drop in operating profit, by reducing interest
expenses and adjusting some liabilities from its acquisition
last year of Tiger International Inc. In all, it reported
$14.4 million less of what it calls "other expenses" in the
period, compared with a year ago.
   For the year, Federal had net income of $115.8 million, or
$2.18 a share, down 31% from $184.6 million, or $3.53 a
share, in fiscal 1989. Revenue rose 36% to $7.02 billion from
$5.17 billion.
   Mr. Murphy estimated that Federal had losses of $150
million in its most recent fiscal year from overseas
expansion. Much of those losses came in Europe, where freight
forwarders -- the middlemen that book freight transportation
for clients -- have been reluctant to use the heavy-cargo
operation that Federal acquired with Tiger, because they view
Federal as a potential competitor in door-to-door service.
   "Forwarders are watching the situation very, very
closely," said Manfred Engst, executive vice president of
Schenkers International Forwarders Inc., Frankfurt, West
Germany, a freight broker and a large Federal customer.
   On Federal's trans-Pacific routes, cargo shipments have
fallen nearly 20% since February, analysts say, because of
sluggish import demand in the U.S. that's affecting all
carriers.
   Thomas Oliver, Federal's senior vice president,
international, said the company has found that for every 1%
that the U.S. economy slows down, imports drop 10%. He said
Federal's business is slowly improving in Europe, but still
has a long way to go.
   Mr. Oliver refused to predict when Federal's struggling
international operations would become profitable, saying
only, "I'm quite positive about what we can accomplish in the
next few years."
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Federal closed at $45.50, up 87.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Caution Urged in Assessing
   Tax Debt of Foreign Firms
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES FORGN
</CO>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration's top tax official
urged Congress to use "extreme caution" before concluding
that U.S. subsidiaries of foreign companies are evading U.S.
taxes.
   Testifying on the second day of hearings at a House Ways
and Means subcommittee, Kenneth Gideon, assistant Treasury
secretary for tax policy, said "it might be tempting to
infer" from data that foreign-controlled firms are illegally
shifting income out of the U.S. by paying excessive prices in
transactions with their overseas parents. But he said there
may be other explanations for the low tax bills, such as
"start-up expenses, acquisition indebtedness, the age of the
investment."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Nevertheless, Mr. Gideon said, "There's certainly data
there to indicate we should be looking carefully at the
transfer-pricing practices of foreign firms."
   The hearings follow a nine-month investigation by the
subcommittee of 36 U.S. subsidiaries of foreign automobile,
electronics and motorcycle companies. On Tuesday,
subcommittee investigators testified that more than half of
the companies paid little or no tax over a 10-year period,
largely by inflating the prices they paid their parents for
goods, services and technology to reduce their U.S. incomes.
U.S. tax law requires companies to charge market prices in
transactions with related firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
