<LP>
   THE FED IS POISED to ease interest rates modestly in
response to growing evidence of a credit crunch, Greenspan
said. The Fed chief also said the agency is working to boost
capital rules for banks and to toughen their enforcement.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stocks and bonds rallied on Greenspan's statement on
interest rates. The Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 37.13
points to close at 2969.80, a record. The dollar declined.
   ---
   GTE and Contel agreed to merge in a $6.2 billion stock
swap that would create the biggest local-exchange phone
company in the U.S. and combine two large cellular units.
Contel's stock soared, but GTE shares slipped.
   ---
   GOP budget negotiators have discussed giving up on a
capital-gains tax cut if Democrats stop seeking higher income
taxes for the rich.
   ---
   Saudi Arabia accepted a temporary reduction in its share
of OPEC output after winning a pledge from other exporters to
freeze production. Oil prices surged, as did oil stocks.
   ---
   Motel 6 agreed to be acquired by Accor for nearly $1.3
billion. The deal will make the French buyer one of the
world's largest lodging companies.
   ---
   Castle &amp; Cooke may sell Dole Food rather than spin it off.
Several companies are interested in the unit.
   ---
   Computer Associates stock plunged nearly 40% after the
firm said it will post lower first-quarter revenue.
   ---
   Double hulls would be required for new oil tankers, and
phased in for most existing ones, under legislation approved
by legislative conferees.
   ---
   Big retailers reported a 5.8% average sales gain in June,
as sunny weather boosted buying of apparel. Wal-Mart, K mart
and Dayton Hudson's Target did particularly well, while
Limited's same-store sales fell.
   ---
   A mistrial was declared on 26 charges against John A.
Mulheren Jr. after the jury deadlocked. The judge let stand
his conviction Tuesday on conspiracy and securities fraud.
   ---
   Blinder Robinson and its chairman were sued by the SEC for
$20 million in profit from alleged illegal stock activity by
the penny-stock firm.
   ---
   Kubota was sued by the founders of a U.S. computer firm,
who say the Japanese giant appropriated their technology
through a minority stake.
   ---
   Soybean futures are expected to rally today after the
government raised its estimate of exports and trimmed its
projection for stockpiles.
   ---
   Curtiss-Wright declared a $30 special dividend and pledged
to focus on manufacturing rather than investing.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 211,510,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2969.80, up 37.13; transportation 1164.96, up 9.67; utilities
206.49, up 1.70.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3432.80, up
22.50.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.00, up 0.64; spot
index 132.38, off 0.08.
   Dollar: 147.30 yen, off 1.20; 1.6340 marks, off 0.0220.
