<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Unocal UXP Partnership Units Fall Sharply
   Ahead of Planned Conversion to Corporation
   ----
   By Roger Lowenstein
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   UXP UCL
</CO>
<IN>
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Are the public investors in Union Exploration
Partners being shortchanged by Unocal?
   The Los Angeles-based oil and gas giant created the
partnership and sold a small stake to the public in 1985 as
part of a plan to ward off a raid by T. Boone Pickens Jr.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Unocal put some of its choicest gas-producing properties
in the partnership, known as UXP. And though Unocal held a
controlling 95% stake, UXP appealed to small investors who
wanted a steady stream of tax-deferred cash payments.
   UXP did make big distributions, but prices of the publicly
traded units, initially $22 each, headed south as oil and gas
prices slumped. The cruncher came in June, when Unocal
disclosed that on Aug. 1, it will convert UXP into a
corporation.
   In the month since then, the market value of UXP has
plunged to less than $12 a unit from $18.25, though the units
have regained ground this week to $13.
   "The new company will have exactly the same assets, and
the price has fallen to 13 from 18. Can capital markets be
that inefficient?," wonders PaineWebber analyst Bryan
Jacoboski.
   Capital markets, in fact, recognize that the income from
UXP will plunge too. Previously, it was expected to pay about
$1.65 a unit this year. But the new company expects to pay a
yearly corporate dividend, fully taxable, of only 40 cents a
share.
   Unocal has contingently promised to compensate holders for
any drop of as much as $3 in the unit price from $18.20. At
current prices, holders are still out more than $2 a unit, or
$27 million for the 12 million units in public hands.
   Steven Spence, a stockbroker for PaineWebber in Portland,
Ore., has written the Securities and Exchange Commission,
claiming that Unocal violated its fiduciary duty by taking an
action that caused the market value of the units to decline.
   Clients of the PaineWebber branch own 1.5 million units.
They are also unhappy because Unocal's original prospectus
didn't mention the possibility of such a conversion. In
Unocal's behalf, the prospectus didn't preclude a conversion.
   Salomon Brothers, Unocal's paid adviser, says the
conversion is fair to unitholders. Unocal says it can't
comment until a filing is approved by the SEC.
   Analysts say Unocal's privately expressed position is that
investors should "calm down and be patient." Although unit
prices have dropped as income-oriented investors have
deserted UXP, Unocal is planning a road show to pitch the new
vehicle to large investors. The company's position, one
investor says, is that "it's only a function of time before
institutions understand the new vehicle."
   Analysts can see why a unitholder would be griping, but
they are hardly shedding tears. "Anyone who bought the units
knew that 95% were owned by Unocal," notes Kidder Peabody's
Marc Cohen.
   With only 5% of the new company's shares to be traded
publicly, analysts say they doubt whether institutions will
jump in. "The float is small," says Prescott Ball &amp; Turben's
Bruce Lazier. "That's why I think this is a first step."
   The Street is betting that, some time after UXP is
converted, Unocal will sell off more UXP shares to raise
cash. With 29% of Unocal's U.S. oil reserves and 59% of its
U.S. gas reserves, UXP is a large entity with a tiny public
float. Enlarging that float would be an attractive way to
raise money for drilling for oil and gas.
   The oil giant seems motivated by a desire to invest more
in exploration. "Corporations are more efficient vehicles for
reinvestment than partnerships," its filing says.
Partnerships, however, are better suited to paying money out
to holders than taking it in.
   When the partnership was formed, raiders such as Mr.
Pickens were arguing that exploration was a waste, that "the
cheapest oil" was on the New York Stock Exchange. The best
oil companies could do, it was said, was to pay out their
cash flow. Hence, Unocal and others rushed to form
partnerships.
   But Salomon analyst Bernard Picchi says exploration
opportunities in the '90s loom large. UXP, he says, has
"enormous exploration potential" because its Gulf of Mexico
gas properties are long-lived and close to a network of
pipelines. Drilling in the ground has again become cheaper
than drilling on the stock exchange, he quips.
   Thus, Mr. Picchi sees Unocal's move as the beginning of
the end for other oil partnerships. "By 1995, none of them
are likely to exist."
   ---
   Union Exploration Partners
   (NYSE; Symbol: UXP)
                                                                                                       

   Business: Oil and gas exploration
                                                                                                       

   Year ended Dec. 31, 1989:
   Revenue: $753.2 million
   Net income: $253.7 million; $1.03 a unit
                                                                                                       

   First quarter, March 31, 1990:
   Per-unit earnings: 28 cents vs. 43 cents
                                                                                                       

   Average daily trading volume:
   34,552 units
                                                                                                       

   Common units outstanding: 245.7 million
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Iceland Has Elves,
   Who Live in Rocks,
   Nowhere to Be Seen
   ---
   Roads Are Diverted to Avoid
   Disturbing Elf Dwellings;
   `Odd Shapes in the Stone'
   ----
   By Tony Horwitz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   EGILSSTATHIR, Iceland -- It is a mile between farms in
this bleak outpost of fog and stone, but just a few paces to
the nearest hidden home.
   "A family moved in here years ago," says Helgi
Hallgrimsson, tapping a large boulder. "They raise cows, I
think." A family down the road herds sheep. They live in a
tree trunk. Generally, though, elves prefer stones. "It is
easier to find such housing," Mr. Hallgrimsson says, standing
on a hill that is bare except for a few Siberian pines.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Returning to his own simple farmhouse, Mr. Hallgrimsson
dines on bread made with sheep's blood, and curdled milk
mixed with moss. Asked if the rock dwellers eat similar fare,
he responds: "Probably so. But you know, they have never
invited me to visit."
   Mr. Hallgrimsson's neighbors are "huldufolk," a word
meaning "hidden people." They also are known as "alfar," or
elves. While Iceland isn't the only country with elves --
Ireland and Sweden have them, too -- few are so accommodating
to unseen citizens. Icelandic highways dogleg to skirt large
rocks, lest engineers dislodge the occupants of "enchanted
spots." Farmers politely leave fields unplowed because hidden
people need hay for their hidden cows. Huldufolk homes appear
on environmental-impact statements, and factory construction
can sometimes halt while elves find someplace else to live.
   "The only thing we haven't done is give huldufolk the
vote," says Stefan Stefansson, a fisherman in Reykjavik, the
nation's capital. Like many Icelanders, he is slippery on the
subject of elves. "Do I believe in huldufolk?" he asks,
staring into his beer. "I am one."
   When more than 900 people were asked the question in a
University of Iceland survey, 55% said the existence of
huldufolk (and fairies) is possible, probable or certain.
Only 10% answered, "impossible." Erlendur Haraldsson, the
psychologist who conducted the survey, wasn't surprised. Nor
does he think Icelanders are particularly superstitious.
"This isn't America," he says. "We have very few UFOs."
   If aliens ever should land here, they would no doubt feel
at home. When work began last year on an asphalt path in
Reykjavik, surveyors' instruments vanished and computers
developed glitches. The landscape architect directing the
project suspected supernatural mischief. She called in a
well-known psychic, Erla Stefansdottir, to investigate.
   Visiting the site, the 53-year-old piano teacher pats the
top of a rock mottled with lichen. "Just knocking to see if
anyone is home," she says. Thereupon a man with a long beard
and breeches emerges from the rock -- visible to her though
not to this reporter. "He's laughing at us," she says. "He
thinks we're crazy to be standing here staring at him."
   On her advice, the city rerouted the path to skirt this
and another inhabited rock. In the nearby town of Kopavogur,
"Elf Hill Road" narrows to one lane as it passes a rocky
outcropping. An attempt last year to widen the road ended
abruptly when a new jackhammer broke on the first day of
work. Town officials refer to the unseen rock dweller on an
adjoining lot as "the old man at No. 102."
   Elves in Iceland are as old as the hills. According to
Nordic lore, some of them are hills. Elves arrived in Iceland
with the Vikings and Celtic slaves who settled here 1,000
years ago. Extreme isolation, and Iceland's sagas and oral
lore, kept supernatural beliefs alive. So did Iceland's weird
landscape. Bubbling with volcanoes, geysers and boiling mud
pits, Iceland is so lunar in parts that it has been used to
train astronauts.
   Iceland also is sparsely populated, with just 250,000
people occupying an area the size of Ohio. "In such a lonely
place, it is natural to fill out the landscape with elves,"
says Hallfredur Eiriksson, a leading Icelandic folklorist.
   Perhaps it is only natural that Icelandic elves resemble
humans, rather than the dwarfish, often malevolent goblins of
Scandinavian legend. Country huldufolk fish for herring,
raise sheep and attend church, just like other folk. And in a
society so peaceful that it has no army and few police
stations open on weekends, humans and huldufolk usually get
on well. Midwives have told Mr. Eiriksson about delivering
elf babies. Farmers say they have milked elf cows. Sometimes,
the two peoples fall in love, though affairs of the heart
often end badly.
   "It should be nice to have invisible in-laws, but really
it can create problems," says Mr. Eiriksson.
   Icelanders who are skeptical about elves treat the issue
delicately, as an American parent might field a child's
questions about Santa Claus. Haukur Gudmasson, a Shell Oil
salesman, is that rare Icelander who openly declares: "This
talk of huldufolk is nonsense." But, later in the
conversation, he recalls his 16 years in the merchant marine:
"Whenever I worked in the engine room," he says, "there was
another man -- not a real person -- there at my side." The
fellow was blond, wore a wool sweater and helped Mr.
Gudmasson with his work. Could he have been an elf? The
salesman bristles. "A ghost, maybe," he says. "But I
certainly don't go around seeing people in stones."
   Very few Icelanders do, but almost everyone can tell when
elves are about. Guthmunder Svafarsson, a veteran road
engineer, remembers the time he tried to blast through a
ridge while building a highway in the north. Bulldozers broke
down, and residents had nightmares. Normally, he says, a
simple elf-diversion would have done the trick. But this was
a major project, with an added complication: The rock wasn't
merely occupied, it was cursed.
   "We had discussions," the engineer says, by which he means
that a medium contacted both the elves and the deceased woman
who had hexed the rock. They were of one mind: Build over,
rather than through, the ridge. "I was furious," says Mr.
Svafarsson, who has encountered elf delays on other
occasions. "But what could I do? Everyone except me believed
in elves."
   Work on a fish-meal factory in nearby Akureyri also ceased
when elves sabotaged machines. In that case, however, talks
proved fruitful. The elves said construction could resume,
but that they first needed three weeks to vacate. Workmen
obliged.
   Through one man's efforts, elf advocacy is becoming a
sophisticated science. Mr. Hallgrimsson, the farmer in stony
Egilsstathir, began his career as a botanist, specializing in
mushrooms. While gathering fungi, he collected folk tales as
well. Drawing on oral testimony and written records, he now
is mapping Iceland's supernatural population.
   He presented road builders in Akureyri with a detailed map
of the elf harbor and metropolis their highway would bisect
(they built it anyway). When plans were drawn up for an
aluminum smelter, which has yet to be built, he inserted a
map with a legend that includes: "Huldufolk Dwellings, Other
Spirits, Odd Shapes in the Stone." In Egilsstathir, he has
also gathered data on dwarfs, trolls and a humped serpent,
called "the Worm," that lives in a lake.
   Mr. Hallgrimsson, a 55-year-old with merry blue eyes and a
pointy gray beard, looks rather like a storybook elf himself.
Oddly, given all his research, he remains an agnostic on the
question of whether huldufolk truly exist. As a scientist, he
is most comfortable with empirical evidence, and so far all
his information is secondhand.
   "It would be enough," he says wistfully, "to see one elf."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Saudis Appear to Have Won Campaign
   To Freeze OPEC Output, Boosting Prices
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Saudi Arabia apparently has succeeded in its campaign to
lift world oil prices.
   After winning pledges from other oil exporters to freeze
output at current levels, Saudi Arabia, the chief producer in
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, agreed to
a temporary reduction in its percentage of OPEC output. That
agreement made room for a bigger quota for the United Arab
Emirates, a chronic overproducer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Finally, the kingdom nudged the UAE into accepting the new
quota of 1.5 million barrels a day that it had previously
rejected.
   These developments set the stage for a likely new
production agreement when OPEC's oil ministers meet late this
month in Geneva, Switzerland. The expected accord would
establish a new output ceiling of 22.5 million barrels a day
-- an increase of 400,000 barrels aimed at accommodating the
UAE's return to the fold.
   Oil prices exploded on the news. In the U.S. stock market,
oil stocks rallied sharply for the second consecutive
session. Some oil prices surged as much as $1 a barrel. In
the U.S. futures market, crude oil for August delivery
settled 99 cents higher at $18.46 a barrel.
   Petroleum prices had dropped by one-third since the
beginning of the year because of an oil glut brought on by
OPEC overproduction. But prices began firming this week as
Saudi Arabia hosted a meeting of five Persian Gulf oil
ministers to try to lay the groundwork for a solution to the
output problem.
   Among the ministers at the Jeddah meeting were those from
Kuwait and the UAE, the two nations that have been blamed for
much of the overproduction that has kept OPEC output well
above 23 million barrels a day.
   In a grueling 12-hour session, according to people
attending the meeting, Kuwait's new oil minister pledged to
hold that country's output to its quota of 1.5 million
barrels a day no matter what the UAE might do. Kuwait has
been producing about 1.7 million barrels a day, and the UAE,
about two million a day.
   "That took care of 50% of the problem," said a source
close to Saudi Arabia's oil-policy decision makers. "The
other 50% was the UAE," he said -- until late yesterday, when
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia made a phone call to Sheik Zayyed
Bin Sultan Al-Nayyan, the president of the emirates.
   The UAE has been insisting on a quota of two million
barrels a day, its current level of output. OPEC had been
offering it a quota of 1.5 million to put it at parity with
Kuwait, but the emirates rejected that, and so OPEC had
continued to list the UAE at its old quota of 1.1 million
barrels a day.
   Shortly after King Fahd's phone call, Mana Said Otaiba,
the UAE oil minister, told Hisham Nazer, the Saudi oil
minister, that he agreed to a national quota of 1.5 million.
According to Mr. Nazer, OPEC's Vienna-based headquarters will
be informed of the UAE decision today.
   It's hardly likely the UAE will quickly cut output by
one-fourth, to 1.5 million barrels from two million. But even
if it only trims 200,000 barrels a day, that reduction
combined with cuts expected from Kuwait would drop OPEC's
daily output to 23 million barrels or less for the first time
this year. Oil economists say that should satisfy the oil
markets because it's in line with expected demand for OPEC
oil.
   "What they {the Persian Gulf producers} have done is
decide that price should have priority over volume," said
John Lichtblau, president of the Petroleum Industry Research
Foundation.
   In a maneuver not unusual for OPEC, the lower production
level would be obtained by raising the production ceiling.
That ceiling, now 22.1 million barrels a day, is expected to
be boosted to 22.5 million for the third quarter. Then around
Sept. 14 -- which will be the 30th anniversary of OPEC's
formation -- the oil ministers probably will meet again to
establish the ceiling for the fourth quarter.
   "The intention now is to lift the price to September,"
said a senior OPEC delegate from a Middle East producing
country. "Hopefully, by September, all the OPEC members will
be tending to their commitments, and the price will be higher
than $18."
   The oil ministers meeting in Saudi Arabia this week said
earlier that their intent was to raise the price of the OPEC
basket of crudes to "at least" $18 a barrel from the recent
average of $14. OPEC prices usually trail U.S. prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   GTE, Contel Agree in Principle
   To Merge in $6.2 Billion Stock Swap
   ---
   Transaction Would Create
   Largest Local-Exchange
   Telephone Firm in U.S.
   ----
   By Mary Lu Carnevale and Randall Smith
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   CTC GTE CCXLA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   GTE Corp. and Contel Corp. agreed in principle to merge in
a transaction valued at about $6.2 billion that would create
the largest local-exchange telephone company in the U.S.
   The proposed exchange of stock also would consolidate two
large cellular-phone businesses, expand
telecommunications-satellite opportunities and eventually
could yield more efficient services to local customers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The memorandum of understanding approved by the boards of
both companies calls for GTE to issue 1.27 common shares for
each of Contel's 160 million common shares outstanding, or a
total of about 200 million GTE shares. The exchange would be
tax-free to shareholders.
   In response to the announcement, Contel's stock soared in
active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, closing at
$35.125, up $7.125. The news initially sent GTE stock
tumbling $3.375 to $27.625 a share, but it recovered steadily
throughout the day, closing down $1.25 at $29.75. The merger
is likely to lead to dilution in GTE shares next year, and
some analysts figure it could be about 10%. The news also
sparked trading interest in several other telephone-company
stocks.
   Spokesmen for both companies said a definitive agreement
is expected to be drawn up and approved by their boards
within a few weeks. The merger could be completed by year
end, they indicated. In the meantime, the companies must
obtain permission from stockholders and state and federal
regulators, as well as antitrust clearance from the Justice
Department. The companies said they anticipate no problems in
winning the various approvals.
   Analysts said the proposed merger is likely to kick off a
major round of consolidation within the local-exchange
telephone industry. "Telephone access lines are vastly
undervalued by investors," said Jack Grubman, a PaineWebber
analyst. "Clearly, this merger is a groundbreaking event as
the first combination of major telephone companies."
   The combined company, which would operate as GTE Corp.,
would have a total of 17.7 million access lines, more than
any of the seven giant regional Bell companies. And its
cellular-phone operations would serve about 50 million
potential subscribers.
   James L. "Rocky" Johnson, GTE's chairman, would be
chairman and chief executive officer of the combined company.
Charles R. Lee, GTE's president and chief operating officer,
would retain those titles after the merger, the companies
said in a joint announcement.
   Contel's chairman, Charles Wohlstetter, and its vice
chairman, John L. Segall, would become vice chairmen of the
combined company. Donald W. Weber, Contel president and chief
executive, "will occupy a key position in the merged entity,"
according to the statement.
   GTE, based in Stamford, Conn., with operations in 46
states and 41 nations, posted 1989 earnings of $1.4 billion,
or $4.16 a share, on revenue of $17.4 billion. Atlanta-based
Contel, which has telephone operations in 30 states and
cellular operations in 36 metropolitan areas, had earnings of
$287 million, or $1.80 a share, on revenue of $3.1 billion
last year. It operates its cellular systems through a
90%-owned unit, Contel Cellular Inc.
   GTE's Mr. Johnson said in a statement that the combination
"will both position the company strategically and enable us
to exploit more fully the many opportunities for growth that
exist in the world-wide telecommunications marketplace." He
noted that the companies' businesses and organizational
structures complement each other.
   Contel's Mr. Wohlstetter said the merger "will provide the
critical mass and financial strength Contel has sought in
order to accelerate the many initiatives we have taken
recently" in telecommunications. Earlier this year, the
company bought metropolitan cellular properties in the South
from McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
   For consumers, the combination could eventually lead to
more sophisticated telephone services, such as computerized
information services. But for both companies, the merger is
certain to create some short-term havoc. Frank Governali, an
analyst for First Boston, who changed his recommendation on
GTE to "sell," said that meshing the companies is likely to
be a long, costly project.
   "GTE just announced a major restructuring of its own
telephone operations and expects it to take four years," he
said. "Absorbing Contel will be as long and as expensive." In
the end, he said, the merger "makes them a bigger company,
but I don't think it gives them a better strategic position."
   Others noted some regulatory risks for Contel. In states
where both companies operate, Contel's business is generally
small. "They're invisible to regulators and can earn a high
rate of return," said Edward Greenberg of Morgan Stanley. "As
part of GTE, they will be subject to greater regulatory
scrutiny."
   One reason the companies chose to announce the memorandum
of understanding before reaching a definitive agreement,
traders said, may have been to test Wall Street's reaction.
If GTE investors disliked the idea, for example, the
companies could still modify terms of the proposal or scrap
it.
   A benefit for Contel holders could be a higher dividend.
GTE's current payout is $1.46 a share annually, compared with
Contel's $1.10. The GTE spokesman said the merger plan would
have no effect on the board's dividend decision, noting that
GTE has increased its dividend in 34 of the past 35 years.
   Contel has been in the middle of a $400 million equity
offering to help finance its $1.3 billion purchase of
cellular operations from McCaw. That offering would now be
scrapped. GTE had a stock-market capitalization of nearly $20
billion before this agreement, and the new company's
capitalization would be roughly $26 billion.
   Word of the proposed merger pushed up stocks of other
independent local exchange carriers, including Southern New
England Telephone Co., Centel Corp., and even McCaw, which
last year agreed to buy Lin Broadcasting Corp. in a bold
expansion.
   Meanwhile, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it is reviewing
the securities of GTE for possible downgrade and those of
Contel for a possible boost. The move affects $11.2 billion
of debt at GTE and its subsidiaries and $3.7 billion at
Contel and its units.
   The senior debt ratings for the parent companies currently
are single-A-minus at GTE and triple-B at Contel.
   ---
                     Telephone Merger
                                                                                                       

                 How the Companies Compare
                                                                                                       

   All dollar amounts in billions
                                                                                                       

                                       GTE         Contel
                                                                                                       

   1989 Revenue                      $17.42         $3.11
                                                                                                       

   1989 Net Income                     3.19          0.29
                                                                                                       

