<HL>
   How Poll Was Conducted
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   DJ GE
</CO>
<LP>
   The Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll was based on
nationwide telephone interviews of 1,555 registered voters
conducted July 6 through July 11 by the polling organizations
of Peter Hart and Robert Teeter.
   The sample was drawn from 315 randomly selected geographic
points in the continental United States. Each region of the
country was represented in proportion to its population.
Households were selected by a method that gave all telephone
numbers, listed and unlisted, an equal chance of being
included. One registered voter, 18 years or older, was
selected from each household by a procedure to provide the
correct number of male and female respondents. The results of
the survey were minimally weighted by race and party
identification to assure that the poll accurately reflects
registered voters nationwide.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chances are 19 of 20 that if all registered voters in the
U.S. had been surveyed using the same questionnaire, the
findings would differ from these poll results by no more than
2.6 percentage points in either direction. The margin of
error for subgroups would be larger.
   An additional number of black respondents were also
included. This oversample does not change the results of the
overall survey, but aids in analyzing black voters' views.
The margin of error among blacks in this survey is plus or
minus 6.7 percentage points.
   (See related Story: "Tricky Issue: Thrift Scandal, Viewed
As Political Dynamite, Is Slow to Detonate --- Democrats Are
Being Hurt As Much as Republicans; Public Blames the S&amp;Ls ---
`Dirty Laundry on Both Sides'" -- WSJ July 13, 1990)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Emigrant Savings Files
   To Raise Its Holdings
   In Greater New York
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GRTR
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Emigrant Savings Bank filed with the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. for permission to raise its 9.9%
stake in Greater New York Savings Bank to not more than 25%
and for a change of control in Greater New York.
   The filing said Emigrant is considering ways to increase
Greater New York's share price. But it added that neither
Emigrant nor its owners, Seymour and Paul Milstein, have any
current plans that would result in a merger, reorganization
or liquidation of Greater New York, nor any plans to change
the board of directors or the management of the company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Greater New York said it is studying the
regulatory filing and will make "an appropriate response" to
regulatory authorities. Officials of Emigrant didn't return
telephone calls.
   In January 1989, Greater New York rejected an offer by
Emigrant to purchase the 90.1% of the stock it didn't own for
$16 a share, or about $182 million. At the time, Greater New
York officials said the offer "represents a thinly disguised
attempt by Emigrant to have its 9.9% position in our stock
bought out after having put us into play. We won't be
manipulated and expect that the market won't be fooled."
   Since then, Greater New York has adopted a shareholder
rights plan and a leveraged employee stock ownership plan,
both aimed at deterring hostile takeover bids.
   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Greater
New York closed at $6.25, up $1.125.
</TEXT>
