<HL>
   SEC Wants Brokers
   To Give Warning
   On Capital Shifts
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission, in
its first regulatory reaction to the collapse of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., proposed rules that would force
brokerage firms to give regulators early warning of large
capital movements.
   The agency also voted to propose rules sharply limiting
the flexibility of money-market funds. The measure would
restrict the amount of lower-quality holdings by the funds,
which are held by 21 million investors for a total of $450
billion, according to SEC figures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The brokerage proposal would revise the agency's so-called
net capital rule, which requires brokerage firms to keep
certain amounts of their assets liquid in case of emergency.
But the SEC is concerned that it has no requirement for
brokerage firms to notify regulators before moving large
amounts of capital. Chairman Richard Breeden called the plan
a "smoke detector" for major problems at brokerage firms.
   That situation came into play earlier this year in the
collapse of Drexel. The parent company, desperately trying to
fend off a liquidity crunch caused by its junk-bond
portfolio, took several infusions of capital from its
brokerage subsidiary. As Drexel's crisis came to a head, the
firm tried to shift more capital to the parent, a move that
would have put the brokerage unit below the net capital
requirement.
   The SEC blocked the move, citing a potential risk to the
brokerage system, and Drexel was forced to file for
bankruptcy-law protection.
   Market regulation director Richard Ketchum said the agency
was concerned that a similar situation "may arise in other
broker-dealers, particularly those in a large holding-company
structure."
   Yesterday's rule proposal would require brokerage firms to
notify the SEC two days before withdrawing certain levels of
net capital. The SEC would then have the authority to bar the
firm from making such a move. The rule also would create an
additional standard designed to limit capital withdrawals for
firms with large securities-trading positions.
   The New York Stock Exchange already has proposed a warning
rule, but that proposal would simply require the exchange to
be notified within 24 hours after a shift of more than 20%
was made. "We don't think that's sufficient for the
commission," Mr. Ketchum said. "Some horses may have left the
barn."
   The money-fund rule, which was expected, comes on the
heels of several recent defaults by issuers of commercial
paper, or short-term corporate borrowings. Money funds hold
huge amounts of commercial paper.
   The proposal would require the funds' prospectus to
clearly state that the holdings aren't insured or guaranteed
by the federal government. Moreover, it would prohibit funds
from investing more than 5% of assets in securities of a
single issuer or in securities rated at less than the highest
quality. It would impose other restrictions on holdings as
well.
   The rule would give "better assurances that safety
expectations of investors can be met," said Gene Gohlke,
acting director of investment management.
   Commissioner Mary Schapiro expressed concern about the
quality of the rating agencies and wondered whether the SEC's
use of the term "high quality" could mislead investors.
Commissioner Philip Lochner said the rule could affect the
commercial-paper market by removing a major buyer. But agency
staffers said they thought it would have only a "minimal
effect" on the commercial-paper market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Retailers Posted
   Average 5.8% Rise
   In Sales for June
   ----
   By Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   WMT KM DH LTD S JCP CHH GPS MA MES HDS MST Z
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Sunny June weather across most of the country boosted
sales of apparel and other seasonal-related items for many of
the nation's largest retailers.
   Although June wasn't an outstanding month for most
retailers, the Merrill Lynch Retail Sales Index of 17 leading
chains showed that revenue increased an average 5.8% against
a 5.2% gain in May. Some analysts had feared that May's poor
results reflected consumer panic, not simply the widespread
cold, gloomy weather that month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts also indicated that much of June's revenue growth
was generated by heavy promotional sales. Many retailers
started the month with inventory they had expected to sell
during May. Top seasonal sellers in June, analysts said,
included air conditioners and pool-related products.
   "We saw some improvement in June, which should enable
retailers to enter the important second half lean and clean,"
said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. He
added: "There are, however, problems ahead. The housing
market is weak, and there are slowing trends in personal
spending. There's also a lack of direction from the fashion
market, which may indicate softening for apparel."
   Retailers that performed particularly well included
Wal-Mart Stores Inc., K mart Corp., and the Target discount
store division of Dayton Hudson Corp. Among the chains with
disappointing results was Limited Inc., whose namesake
Limited division had an estimated 5% decrease in sales for
stores open at least one year.
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Limited
shares closed yesterday at $23, down $2.125.
   "Overall economic growth and consumer spending as a
component of that growth is probably below average, but the
June numbers indicate the economy isn't sinking rapidly into
recession," said Barry Bryant, an analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Mr. Bryant noted that consumers have been particularly
responsive to licensed products this summer. Sales of goods
endorsed by Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles, Dick Tracy, and
"underachiever" Bart Simpson have been strong. "Who would
have believed that the Simpsons would have emerged as giant
counterculture figures in only 90 days?" marveled Mr. Bryant.
   At Wal-Mart, same-store sales were up 14% in June and 12%
for the five months ended June 30 against the like
year-earlier periods. The discounter did particularly well
with men's and children's apparel, as well as food items and
toy products.
   "They were helped because their reporting period included
five Saturdays instead of four Saturdays a year ago," said
Robert Buchanan, an analyst with Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc.
"Still, they are taking market share from lesser competitors.
We're seeing a nationwide trend in which the strong get
stronger in retailing."
   At Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co., the nation's largest retailer,
comparable store sales were up 3.5%. "They did well with
their jazzed-up electronics and appliance departments," said
Mr. Buchanan. "They've begun to give a lot more space in the
stores to those categories, so you'd expect some pop in
sales. They didn't do as well in apparel, which reflects
continued weakness in that area."
   At K mart, comparable store sales grew 4.3% in June.
"Their apparel sales were strong," said Mr. Buchanan. "The
big picture here is that the company's expense structure in
relationship to sales are higher than that of Wal-Mart and
Target. Therefore they can't price as aggressively across the
board."
   Mr. Buchanan expressed surprise that the Limited division
of Limited Inc. showed an estimated 5% decrease in same-store
sales. "They are dropping prices on their Forenza
private-label line of casual sportswear, and that's hurting
them," said Mr. Buchanan. "The line is being replaced with
Paul et Duffier. The transition is causing some unexpected
pain." Same-store sales rose 5.1% at Dayton Hudson; 5% at the
parent Limited; 4.9% at Woolworth Corp; 4.1% at J.C. Penney
Co. and 1% at Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc.
   "The overall trend is that we saw a pick-up in promotions
in June following on an extremely sluggish May," said Janet
Mangano, an analyst with Jesup, Josephthal &amp; Co. "What we saw
were pent-up promotions, not pent-up consumer demands. I'm
expecting disappointing second-quarter earning performances."
   ---
