<HL>
   Your Money Matters:
   Social Security Records Deserve a Check
   ----
   By Karen Slater
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES LABOR
</CO>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Social Security seems like a black hole to many working
Americans. It claims as much as 7.7% of their salaries. Yet
they fear they won't get much back come retirement.
   Compounding the unease: Many people hear nary a word from
the government program in the decades between signing up for
a Social Security number and applying for their benefits.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But Social Security is too important to ignore. Working
people can and should bridge the gap of silence -- to get
benefits estimates that can help in planning for retirement
and evaluating insurance needs, and to ensure that they
ultimately get every penny for which they're eligible.
   The Social Security Administration recommends that people
check the agency's records of their earnings every three
years or so. Omissions "aren't common, but when they happen
they can be a nightmare," a spokesman says.
   John Rother, director of legislation and public policy for
the American Association of Retired Persons, learned
first-hand the value of checking Social Security's records.
He requested his information a few years back just to see
what AARP members could expect. What he found was a two-year
gap when his earnings as a Senate staffer weren't recorded at
all.
   Such gaps could saddle a person with a lower retirement
benefit than deserved because of the way Social Security
benefits are calculated. They're based on people's average
earnings in their 35 highest-paid years, translating all
figures into today's dollars. People could be penalized, for
example, if some high earnings at the peak of their careers
are omitted and replaced in the calculation by zeros or by
pay from years when they were just starting out.
   Less than 1% of eligible wages aren't credited to people's
records, the Social Security Administration says. And
correcting an error is fairly easy if a person knows it
exists: Just contact Social Security with W-2 forms or other
records that verify wages and Social Security taxes for the
period in question. Unfortunately, many don't discover
omissions until retirement age, if at all.
   Back in 1987, the General Accounting Office reported that
$58.5 billion in earnings between 1978 and 1984 apparently
had been left off people's Social Security records. Those
were wages that employers had reported to the Internal
Revenue Service, but not to Social Security.
   A stepped-up effort by the Social Security Administration
to resolve such discrepancies has resulted in $36 billion of
those earnings being credited to people's records. But the
agency spokesman says the remainder hasn't been credited, in
many cases because Social Security couldn't find the
individual or the company involved.
   Finding out about what's in your Social Security earnings
record is easy. Stop by a Social Security office or call
toll-free (800/234-5SSA) to get a request form for a free
Personal Earnings and Benefit Estimate Statement (Pebes).
Answer a few questions on the form, mail it in, and get the
Pebes in about four weeks.
   That same statement also contains benefits estimates,
including those that would be paid if a person dies or
becomes disabled. Those figures are important in evaluating
life insurance and disability insurance needs.
   "Social Security isn't just a retirement program. You're
buying enormous lifetime protection," says Judy Schub, a
lobbyist for the AARP.
   Still, the estimates of retirement benefits may be the
most valuable part of the Pebes statement for people starting
to think about leaving the work force. That's a new feature
Social Security added about two years ago.
   The statement shows the benefits that people might expect,
expressed in today's dollars, if they retire at three
different ages. People can look at those figures as a
percentage of their current salary to get a sense of how much
of their working income Social Security might replace.
   One message that is likely to come through very clearly is
that Social Security alone is far from enough.
   The government program will generally replace about 60% of
earnings for a worker who has always earned the minimum wage,
but only about 28% for someone who has always earned the
maximum pay covered by Social Security -- currently $51,300.
The percentage is even lower for people earning more.
   Meanwhile, a rule of thumb is that retirees, to be
comfortable, need income equal to 70% of their final pay.
Some will need less. But others will require 100% of their
working income in the early years of retirement, at least if
they want to reach goals such as traveling a lot or
maintaining two homes, says Cleveland financial planner Karen
Spero.
   Keep in mind that the benefit figures in the Pebes are
only estimates. "The closer a person is to retirement, the
more accurate those estimates will be," says Malcolm A.
Makin, a Westerly, R.I., planner. The actual payouts will
depend on people's earnings between now and retirement and,
of course, on any changes in Social Security's benefit
formulas.
   It's also important to understand some of the assumptions
that underlie the figures. For instance, when Social Security
projects a person's benefit at age 62, age 65 and age 70, the
agency is assuming that the person keeps working to those
ages -- not that he or she would quit earlier and delay
collecting benefits.
   Even people who don't ask for Pebes reports may eventually
find something like them in their mailboxes. A law passed
last year requires the Social Security Administration by the
year 2000 to send people their earnings records and in some
cases benefits estimates every other year.
   Meanwhile, getting a Pebes report may give some people a
needed push to start retirement planning.
   People should begin to analyze their finances 10 to 15
years before they expect to retire, advises Dallas Salisbury,
president of the Employee Benefit Research Institute in
Washington.
   But when do they really do it? "Eighteen to 36 months
before they plan to retire, if they are really behaved," Mr.
Salisbury says. "And right after retirement if they are
typical."
   ---
                  Social Security's Role
                   In Retirement Income
                                                                                                       

   Sources of income, on average, for retirees with at least
$20,000 in annual income in 1986
                                                                                                       

   Investments ...........................  34%
                                                                                                       

   Earned Income .........................  24%
                                                                                                       

   Social Security .......................  21%
                                                                                                       

   Pensions ..............................  19%
                                                                                                       

   Other .................................   2%
                                                                                                       

   Source: Social Security Administration
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Senate Panel
   Rejects Funds
   For MX Trains
   ---
   Decision Against Missiles
   Is Blow for Bush Policy,
   Points to Political Rift
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Armed Services Committee, racing
to complete a $289 billion Pentagon spending bill, decided
against providing any money to put nuclear-tipped MX missiles
on specially equipped trains.
   The committee's MX decision, coming as the lawmakers met
behind closed doors, repudiated a major building block of the
Bush administration's nuclear-weapons policies and showed a
widening rift between Democrats and Republicans on the panel.
Details of the bill, which were still being hammered out late
last night, are scheduled to be announced today.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The White House did receive some good news when the
committee voted to maintain Pentagon spending for the
Strategic Defense Initiative at this year's level of about
$3.5 billion, according to lawmakers and their aides. The
panel also agreed to keep the embattled B-2 Stealth bomber
alive by authorizing the purchase of another pair of the
radar-evading planes in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1.
   All of the important decisions are bound to be debated
again on the Senate floor. The House version of the bill is
expected to reject deployment of the mobile MX missile too,
but it is likely to call for lower levels of spending on SDI
and the B-2.
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop (R., Wyo.), one of the leading GOP
advocates of heftier spending for SDI, mobile missiles and
the B-2, said that the important decisions in the Senate
panel "came on straight party-line votes. It's all being done
by rote."
   The committee was so divided that some GOP lawmakers even
raised last-minute objections to a politically popular
portion of the bill that would require the military to help
civilian agencies collect global pollution data and focus
part of the Pentagon's research on environmental clean-up
projects. The proposal, pushed by the committee's chairman,
Sam Nunn (D., Ga.), is expected to be part of the final
legislation.
   The spending bill, according to lawmakers, puts the MX and
the smaller, single-warhead Midgetman mobile missile on the
back burner by capping 1991 funding at about $700 million for
both weapons. None of the money, however, could be used for
deployment. In addition, aides said the committee was moving
to cut the administration request for building additional
Trident ballistic-missile submarines and Seawolf attack
submarines.
   As expected, the committee voted to cut 100,000 troops in
1991. That figure could climb higher if Pentagon outlays are
capped at a level less than the committee anticipated. Over
the next five years, Sen. Alan Dixon (D., Ill.) said the
panel envisions slashing some 500,000 troops from the 2.1
million people currently on active duty.
   Sen. Nunn had advocated the $289 billion
spending-authority limit, which would be $18 billion less
than President Bush's January budget request. The committee
sketched out at least another $4 billion in potential cuts
that could take effect if a bipartisan budget agreement
requires further Pentagon spending reductions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0051
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900713-0051.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dingell Criticizes
   Further Purchases
   Of AH-64 Apaches
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   MD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Army is on the verge of buying another $1.5 billion of
AH-64 Apache attack helicopters from McDonnell Douglas Corp.,
despite complaints from military personnel that the aircraft
isn't reliable, according to a congressional panel.
   In a letter dated Wednesday to Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney, Rep. John Dingell (D., Mich.), chairman of the House
subcommittee on oversight and investigations, criticized any
plans to buy more of the helicopters: "I cannot, for the life
of me, fathom the logic of such a decision."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Dingell wrote that although the Army isn't equipped to
provide adequate maintenance support for the nearly 600
Apaches it has on hand, contracts for more AH-64s could be
signed within the next few days. The helicopters cost $14
million each, though Mr. Dingell said the firm has asked for
a large increase in price and profit in the contract talks.
   A spokesman for McDonnell Douglas's helicopter unit
declined to comment. An Army spokeswoman also said she
couldn't comment on any correspondence to Mr. Cheney. But she
did confirm that the service recently wrapped up talks with
McDonnell Douglas for 66 AH-64s. The Pentagon wants, and
Congress has approved funding for, 132 additional Apaches,
which would mean a fleet of 807 by mid-1993.
   Mr. Dingell reiterated a call for the talks with St.
Louis-based McDonnell Douglas to be terminated. Despite the
Army's pledge to add extra manpower and testing to each AH-64
battalion, he said, it "does not have the money" to do so.
   The General Accounting Office, commissioned by Mr. Dingell
to research the Apache problems, has recommended that the
Army not contract for the final 132. He said in his letter
that the GAO's stance "makes even more sense" given that the
Warsaw Pact is "in total disarray."
   Although Army Secretary Michael Stone has maintained that
substantial progess has been made in fixing the AH-64, the
subcommittee continues to cite field reports that the Apache
fails under fire. During the U.S. invasion of Panama in
December, for example, the Apache's electronic components had
to be dried in kitchen ovens after it rained, according to
evidence presented in an April panel hearing.
   After the first day of fighting in Panama, four of the six
AH-64s sent there were grounded when three were shot up with
rifle fire. Meanwhile, the fuel cell in one Apache fizzled
out prior to the attack, and by the time a replacement
arrived, the AH-64 for which it was intended had been
cannibalized for spare parts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900713-0050
</DOCNO>
