   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ford Holdings Co. -- $552 million of 9 1/4% notes, due
July 15, 1997, was priced at 99.871 to yield 9.275%. The
noncallable notes were priced at a spread of 0.79 percentage
point over the Treasury's seven-year note. Rated double-A-2
by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and double-A-minus by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. -- $200 million of 8 3/4%
notes due July 15, 2005, priced at 100.05 to yield 8.734%. In
1994 and 1997, the investor has the option to put the
securities back to the company at par. The notes were priced
at a spread of 0.33 percentage point above the Treasury's
four-year note. Rated double-A-3 by Moody's and
double-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold solely by
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   ITT Financial Corp. -- $150 million of subordinated notes,
due July 15, 2005, was priced at par to yield 8.85%. In 1993
and 1997, the bondholder has the option to put the securities
back to the company at par. The noncallable notes were priced
at a spread of 0.56 percentage point over the Treasury's
three-year note. Rated single-A-2 by Moody's and single-A by
S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through underwriters led by
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   DeKalb Energy Co. -- $75 million of 9 7/8% notes due July
15, 2000, priced at 99.84 to yield 9.90%. The noncallable
notes were priced at a spread of 1.30 percentage points above
the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated Baa-1 by Moody's and
triple-B by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through underwriters
led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Harley-Davidson Inc. -- $50 million of convertible
debentures, due June 30, 2015, was priced at par to yield
7.25%. The debentures are convertible into common stock at
$39.68 a share, representing a 18% conversion premium over
the closing price. Rated Ba-3 by Moody's and single-B by S&amp;P,
the issue will be sold solely by Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
                                                                                                       

                          MORTGAGE
                                                                                                       

   Travelers Mortgage Services Inc. -- $93 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in nine classes by Salomon Brothers Inc. The
offering, Series 1990-10, is backed by 30-year fixed-rate
whole loans with a weighted average coupon rate of about
10.8755% and weighted average remaining term to maturity of
29.92 years. The issue is rated double-A-2 by Moody's and
double-a by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                           OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Province of Nova Scotia -- $300 million of 9 3/8% notes,
due July 15, 2002, was priced at 99.360 to yield 9.465%. The
noncallable notes were priced at a spread of 0.95 percentage
point above the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated single-A-2 by
Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Sumitomo Bank International Finance N.V. (Japanese parent)
-- $700 million of 10-year floating-rate notes at par, via
Sumitomo Finance International. Maturity August 2000. Coupon
floats 0.25 point above three-month London interbank offered
rate for years one to five, then at Libor plus 0.35
percentage point for the next five years. Callable after five
years at par. Guaranteed on a subordinated basis by Sumitomo
Bank Ltd.
   Orient Corp. (Japan) -- $300 million of bonds due Aug. 2,
1994, with equity-purchase warrants, with 4 3/4% coupon at
par, via Nomura International Ltd. Each $5,000 bond carries
one warrant, exercisable from Aug. 16, 1990, through July 22,
1994, to buy shares at an expected premium of 2 1/2% to the
closing price when terms are fixed Wednesday.
   Swedish National Mortgage Corp. (Sweden) -- $200 million
of fungible bonds due May 30, 1995, priced at 100.675 via
sole manager Nomura International Ltd. Fungible from the
payment date with a $300 million deal launched May 14.
   Credit Foncier de France (France) -- 25 billion yen
($169.7 million) of 7 1/8% bonds due Aug. 29, 1995, priced at
101 5/8 to yield 7.19% less full fees, via Yamaichi
International Ltd. Guaranteed by the republic of France. Fees
1 7/8.
   Instituto de Credito Official (Spain) -- 20 billion yen of
floating-rate notes due July 31, 2000, priced at par via IBJ
International Ltd. Coupon will float at 0.50 point below the
Japanese long-term prime rate. Coupon fixed semiannually.
Callable July 31, 1995, and every six months thereafter.
Statutory guarantee by the kingdom of Spain. Fees 0.30.
   Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken (Sweden) -- 200 million
marks ($122.4 million) of 9% bonds due Aug. 10, 2000, priced
at 102 to yield 8.69%, via Deutsche Bank.
   GMAC Australia Finance Ltd. (U.S. parent) -- 75 million
Australian dollars (US$59.8 million) of 14 3/4% bonds due
Aug. 23, 1994, priced at 101.65 to yield 14.78% less fees via
Hambros Bank Ltd. Guaranteed by General Motors Acceptance
Corp. Fees 1 3/4.
   Australian Gas &amp; Lighting Co. (Australia) -- 50 million
Australian dollars of 15.375% bonds due Aug. 31, 1993, priced
at 101.95 to yield 15.18% less fees via Westpac Banking Corp.
Fees 1 1/2.
   Banque Generale du Luxembourg S.A. (Luxembourg) -- 50
million Australian dollars of 20% dual-currency bonds due
Aug. 14, 1991, priced at 101.75, via Bankers Trust
International. Redemption is optional in Australian or
Canadian dollars at a ratio of 87 Canadian cents for each
Australian dollar.
   Dresdner Finance B.V. Amsterdam (German parent) -- 150
million European currency units of 10 1/8% bonds due Aug. 9,
1995, priced at 101.60 via Dresdner Bank. Guaranteed by
Dresdner Bank AG Frankfurt.
